<br>
However, I still sometimes rub enchanters the wrong way if I step in with a mez during an emergency.  There are four situations where I tend to mez.<br>
<br>
1) A mob has been beating on the cleric, and the cleric's life is in danger.<br>
<br>
2) A mob has been beating on the enchanter, and the enchanter's life is in danger.<br>
<br>
3) A mob is beating on me, and my life is in danger.<br>
<br>
4) The enchanter is dead or linkdead.<br>
<br>
With the exception of #4, I have managed to irritate some enchanters by mezzing in those circumstances.<br>
<br>
In case #1, I'll just ignore the enchanter's gripes.  I can fill in for the enchanter, but I can't rez the cleric.<br>
<br>
In case #3, I'll just grit my teeth.  I'm not going to sacrifice my experience just to keep the enchanter happy.<br>
<br>
In case #2, I've found it simplest just to let the enchanter die.  None has ever been greatful for the mez.  None has ever complained that I let them die.  And when they die, no one ever complains that I take over.<br>
<br>
The situation doesn't crop up often.  I work with enchanters maybe 20% of the time.  Most of the time, they never need help.  But the reactions I've gotten (not all the time, but in a majority of the cases) when I have felt compelled to mez ... well, they surprised me.<br>
<br>
Can anyone offer any insight?<br>
<br>
 <p>Staccato Obligato <BR>
<a href=http://www.handofmana.com>Hand of Mana </a><BR>
Troubadour of the 59th Measure <BR>
The Nameless server
